Target: `module/LLMWorkflow/core/StateFile.ps1`

Reason:
- triage `-ErrorAction SilentlyContinue` where it is masking operational cleanup failure instead of handling an optional probe
- keep optional path resolution probes quiet, but surface temp-file cleanup failures in the atomic write failure path

---

## Patch A: keep optional `Resolve-Path` probes as-is

These are acceptable to leave quiet because they are fallback probes, not real failures:

```powershell
$resolvedPath = Resolve-Path -Path $Path -ErrorAction SilentlyContinue
if (-not $resolvedPath) {
    $resolvedPath = $Path
}
```

That pattern appears in several functions and is not the priority target.

## Patch B: surface temp-file cleanup failure in `Write-StateFile`

Current code:

```powershell
catch {
    # Clean up temp file
    if (Test-Path -LiteralPath $tempPath) {
        Remove-Item -LiteralPath $tempPath -Force -ErrorAction SilentlyContinue
    }

    throw "Failed to write state file: $_"
}
```

Replace with:

```powershell
catch {
    # Clean up temp file
    if ($tempPath -and (Test-Path -LiteralPath $tempPath)) {
        try {
            Remove-Item -LiteralPath $tempPath -Force -ErrorAction Stop
        }
        catch {
            Write-Warning "Failed to remove temporary state file '$tempPath' after write failure: $($_.Exception.Message)"
        }
    }

    throw "Failed to write state file: $_"
}
```

Why this matters:
- the write already failed, so silent cleanup failure becomes hidden residue on disk
- this is exactly the kind of invisible operational failure the Priority 0 pass is supposed to expose
- the patch preserves the original throw behavior while adding operator-visible signal

